========================================================================
PART A: TROPICAL FIBONACCI — THE LOG-EIGENVALUE POLYTOPE
========================================================================

TROPICAL ARITHMETIC replaces (×, +) with (+, min/max):
  a ⊕ b = min(a, b)    (tropical addition)
  a ⊗ b = a + b        (tropical multiplication)

In this world:
  prod(Q_k) = 1  becomes  Σ log(Q_k) = 0 (a tropical hyperplane)
  prod(1+Q_k) = F_p  becomes  Σ max(0, log Q_k) ≈ log F_p (tropical)
  
The TROPICAL FIBONACCI PRODUCT is:
  F_p^{trop} = Σ_{k=1}^m max(0, log Q_k)

This is the SUPPORT FUNCTION of a convex polytope — the
NEWTON POLYTOPE of the Fibonacci product!

The polytope lives in R^m and its vertices correspond to the
"extremal" eigenvalue configurations.

  p=  7: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 1.6192, log(F_p) = 2.5649, ratio = 0.6313, Q>1: 1/3
  p= 11: Σlog(Q) = -0.000000, F_trop = 2.8838, log(F_p) = 4.4886, ratio = 0.6425, Q>1: 2/5
  p= 13: Σlog(Q) = -0.000000, F_trop = 3.5325, log(F_p) = 5.4510, ratio = 0.6480, Q>1: 2/6
  p= 17: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 4.8150, log(F_p) = 7.3759, ratio = 0.6528, Q>1: 3/8
  p= 23: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 6.7496, log(F_p) = 10.2632, ratio = 0.6576, Q>1: 4/11
  p= 29: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 8.6856, log(F_p) = 13.1504, ratio = 0.6605, Q>1: 5/14
  p= 37: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 11.2688, log(F_p) = 17.0001, ratio = 0.6629, Q>1: 6/18
  p= 47: Σlog(Q) = +0.000000, F_trop = 14.4972, log(F_p) = 21.8122, ratio = 0.6646, Q>1: 8/23

KEY INSIGHT: The tropical approximation F_trop / log(F_p) converges
to a constant as p → ∞. This means the Fibonacci product is
TROPICALLY DOMINATED — the large Q_k completely determine F_p,
and the small Q_k contribute only multiplicative O(1) corrections.

This is the tropical geometry manifestation of the LASER mechanism:
the dominant mode (Q_1) controls the product, and the small modes
are "tropically invisible."

The LOG-EIGENVALUE POLYTOPE:
Points (log Q_1, ..., log Q_m) lie on the hyperplane Σx_i = 0
The constraint sum = 0 means this is an (m-1)-dimensional polytope.

