========================================================================
PART C: HYPERBOLIC DYNAMICS ON THE MODULAR SURFACE
========================================================================

The transfer matrix T_B = [[3,-1],[1,0]] ∈ SL(2,Z) acts on the
UPPER HALF PLANE H² = {z ∈ C : Im(z) > 0} by Möbius transformation:

  z → (3z - 1) / (z + 0) = 3 - 1/z

This is a HYPERBOLIC ISOMETRY with:
  - Fixed points: z = φ² and z = ψ² (on the real axis)
  - Translation length: ℓ = 2·arccosh(3/2) = 2·log(φ²) = 4·log(φ)
  - Axis: the geodesic from ψ² to φ² on the real line

The MODULAR SURFACE PSL(2,Z)\H² has finite area = π/3.
The geodesic corresponding to T_B has length ℓ = 4·log(φ) ≈ 1.925.

The SELBERG TRACE FORMULA relates:
  Σ (spectral) = Σ (geometric = sum over closed geodesics)

For our tournament:
  The "spectral side" involves the Q_k values (eigenvalue squares)
  The "geometric side" involves Hamiltonian paths (closed geodesics!)

CONNECTION:
  H(T) = p · F_p · A(p)
       = p · (cluster polynomial evaluation) · (geodesic correction)

The AMPLIFICATION A(p) is the ratio of the ACTUAL number of
closed geodesics of length p to the FREE prediction.

Translation length of T_B: ℓ = 4·log(φ) = 1.924847
Area of modular surface: π/3 = 1.047198
Ratio ℓ/(π/3) = 1.838094
Number of primitive geodesics of length ≤ L ~ e^L / L (prime geodesic theorem)
  p= 7: L = 5.77, e^L/L = 55.8, F_p = 13, F_p/(e^L/L) = 0.2331
